    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-06-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="192"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d192">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">762A.00/6–353</note>
                <head>No. 192<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Secretary of State</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d192fn1">A copy of this memorandum was transmitted to
                        President <persName corresp="#p_EGADD1">Eisenhower</persName> on June 3
                        under cover of a memorandum from <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName> which advised the President to read it before he saw
                            <persName corresp="#p_BHAH1">Blankenhorn</persName> on June 4.
                        (762A.00/6–353)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1953-06-03">June 3, 1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BHAH1">Blankenhorn</persName> expressed the following
                    personal views of Dr. <persName corresp="#p_AK1">Adenauer</persName>: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>He felt the need of someone in Bonn with a greater background than
                            that possessed by President <persName corresp="#p_CJP1"
                                >Conant</persName>. He suggested Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RJW1"
                                >Riddleberger</persName> in this connection.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>He explained that Americans presumably connected with the U.S. High
                            Commission were urging a coalition government in Germany. He mentioned a
                            Mr. <persName>Kirchheimer</persName> (?)<note n="2" xml:id="d192fn2">Not
                                further identified.</note> in this connection.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>He strongly urged that prior to the elections we should give Dr.
                                <persName corresp="#p_CJP1">Conant</persName> and later the German
                            Chargé d’Affaires here the title of “Ambassador” in addition, of course,
                            to <persName corresp="#p_CJP1">Conant</persName>’s position as High
                            Commissioner.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Nothing had been accomplished with reference to war criminals and he
                            urged strongly the prompt establishment of at least a two-party U.S.
                            board.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>He urged that an effort be made at Bermuda to agree that in view of
                            the German ratification of the contractuals some of these provisions
                            could provisionally be put into operation while awaiting ratification by
                            the other parties. He said that the Socialists were constantly asserting
                            that <persName corresp="#p_AK1">Adenauer</persName>’s policy had gotten
                            him nowhere with the Allies.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
            </div>
